1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,960
At the start of our three weeks together, I told you to expect a rollercoaster.

2
00:00:04,960 --> 00:00:09,920
And here's the thing. We, on this rollercoaster journey, we have just reached that point

3
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:15,119
when the rollercoaster has got to the very, very top, and you're up there at the top,

4
00:00:15,119 --> 00:00:18,959
and you're looking down, and we're about to take the plunge.

5
00:00:18,959 --> 00:00:24,799
Prepare for the plunge. Prepare for week three, day four. This is a big day.

6
00:00:24,799 --> 00:00:27,840
It's another purple day. It's a day of core skills.

7
00:00:27,840 --> 00:00:32,479
It's the day when we move into the world of swarms and orchestrators.

8
00:00:32,479 --> 00:00:38,479
The time when we go crazy. And it's all about the stages seven and eight

9
00:00:38,479 --> 00:00:43,279
of the Steve Yegge chart that we went through a couple of weeks ago now.

10
00:00:43,279 --> 00:00:47,840
We've already got quite comfortable with the idea that you can run multiple Claude instances.

11
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:50,080
We've done that a bit. We haven't done that in a massive way,

12
00:00:50,080 --> 00:00:51,759
because it's all sort of leading up to this.

13
00:00:51,759 --> 00:00:55,200
But for sure, you've probably experimented with running Claude a few times,

14
00:00:55,200 --> 00:00:58,639
and we had things like that experiment when we had Claude running,

15
00:00:58,639 --> 00:01:00,799
and we had Codex doing the code review.

16
00:01:00,799 --> 00:01:02,479
And so we've seen all of this happening.

17
00:01:02,479 --> 00:01:04,800
And of course, we've worked with sub-agents a fair bit too.

18
00:01:05,519 --> 00:01:09,120
Well, this is the moment when we hit stages seven and eight.

19
00:01:09,120 --> 00:01:13,040
This is the moment when we start to have tons of agents running,

20
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:15,120
which is what you think of as a swarm,

21
00:01:15,120 --> 00:01:18,000
when you have like a huge number of them all doing stuff.

22
00:01:18,559 --> 00:01:22,800
Everything's going on. It seems mad. It's chaos.

23
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:25,279
And then stage eight is when you're like,

24
00:01:25,279 --> 00:01:28,080
okay, maybe we can reel this in.

25
00:01:28,080 --> 00:01:31,919
We can control the chaos by giving the different agents some structure,

26
00:01:31,919 --> 00:01:35,839
by having some in charge of others, by trying to coordinate the work,

27
00:01:35,839 --> 00:01:38,800
but having the LLMs manage the process.

28
00:01:38,800 --> 00:01:41,040
That's what orchestration is about.

29
00:01:41,040 --> 00:01:42,319
And that's what we're going to be doing today.

30
00:01:42,319 --> 00:01:45,599
And as we look between stages seven and eight, swarms versus orchestration,

31
00:01:45,599 --> 00:01:47,839
I don't know that there's necessarily a binary.

32
00:01:47,839 --> 00:01:49,760
We are at this point and we're at that point.

33
00:01:49,760 --> 00:01:53,120
The different solutions we'll be looking at are somewhere on that continuum,

34
00:01:53,120 --> 00:01:56,959
but between being sort of wild swarm with no structure

35
00:01:56,959 --> 00:02:00,720
and extremely organized, structured orchestration.

36
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:05,199
And where you are on that continuum depends a bit on the choices that you make,

37
00:02:05,199 --> 00:02:09,279
how you set it up and how crazy you want to go. As we will see.

38
00:02:09,279 --> 00:02:12,880
All right, we're going to be doing a few different approaches

39
00:02:12,880 --> 00:02:17,600
and I'm going to start right away by looking at Claude's agent teams,

40
00:02:17,600 --> 00:02:21,119
which is the one thing from, I guess, the day one of this week

41
00:02:21,119 --> 00:02:22,639
that we said we'd come back to.

42
00:02:22,639 --> 00:02:24,960
Now's the time. We're coming back to it right here.

43
00:02:24,960 --> 00:02:31,600
So Claude agent teams, first of all, is an experimental feature as of right now.

44
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:33,759
By the time you watch this, maybe it's matured.

45
00:02:33,759 --> 00:02:36,399
Maybe it's no longer just an experimental feature.

46
00:02:36,399 --> 00:02:37,520
But for me, it is.

47
00:02:37,520 --> 00:02:41,279
This is brand new and I'll be going through the experimental side of it.

48
00:02:41,279 --> 00:02:46,320
And maybe you'll look at the docs and see that some of this has become a bit more firm.

49
00:02:46,320 --> 00:02:50,399
But first of all, what are agent teams?

50
00:02:50,399 --> 00:02:54,240
They are ways that you can have multiple Claude code instances,

51
00:02:54,240 --> 00:02:59,440
multiple different Claude codes that are being coordinated in some way.

52
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:01,600
One of them is acting as the team lead.

53
00:03:01,600 --> 00:03:03,759
It is in charge of the whole process.

54
00:03:03,759 --> 00:03:08,559
And its job is to assign out tasks and manage the collaboration between them

55
00:03:08,559 --> 00:03:10,160
in order to achieve a goal.

56
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:14,720
And then the others, the teammates, they're able to work independently

57
00:03:14,720 --> 00:03:18,559
and they're able to interact with each other so they can send each other messages.

58
00:03:18,559 --> 00:03:23,919
And you, as the human in the loop, you can interact with them directly as well.

59
00:03:23,919 --> 00:03:26,000
You don't need to go through the lead.

60
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,360
And this is a massive distinction from sub-agents.

61
00:03:29,360 --> 00:03:32,800
With sub-agents, you can't send a message to a sub-agent.

62
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:36,479
It just exists in order to serve the main Claude code.

63
00:03:36,479 --> 00:03:38,320
And it doesn't really work independently.

64
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:42,880
It only persists for the duration of its task and then its history.

65
00:03:42,880 --> 00:03:45,440
Whereas in this case, these things called teammates,

66
00:03:45,440 --> 00:03:50,000
their teammates, they are all separate Claude codes that are running.

67
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:55,440
Okay, so under what circumstances would you make use of Claude agent teams

68
00:03:55,440 --> 00:03:57,759
instead of, say, sub-agents?

69
00:03:57,759 --> 00:04:00,320
We'll have a direct comparison in a moment.

70
00:04:00,320 --> 00:04:04,720
But here are some examples of use cases that work well for Claude teams.

71
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:09,119
So one of them is if, and this is a sort of simple one that you can imagine,

72
00:04:09,119 --> 00:04:11,199
if you want to research a ton of different things,

73
00:04:11,199 --> 00:04:14,320
like you want to head off and look, you want to look at Wikipedia,

74
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:16,399
and you also want to look at Stack Overflow,

75
00:04:16,399 --> 00:04:18,640
and you also want to look at three other places,

76
00:04:18,640 --> 00:04:23,119
then you could just have a multiple of these team members go off,

77
00:04:23,119 --> 00:04:25,920
do their research independently, working on it,

78
00:04:25,920 --> 00:04:28,320
maybe exchanging information between them,

79
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:30,559
and then come back with all of the results.

80
00:04:30,559 --> 00:04:32,480
And that's something that you can also use sub-agents for,

81
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:34,880
but this is a nice kind of use case.

82
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:37,760
But perhaps a better one, if I may,

83
00:04:37,760 --> 00:04:42,320
is a case where you have independent modules of your system,

84
00:04:42,320 --> 00:04:43,600
and you've got an objective,

85
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:47,519
and you can see a way that different Claude codes could work independently.

86
00:04:47,519 --> 00:04:51,119
And indeed, you could just spawn multiple terminals and run Claude

87
00:04:51,119 --> 00:04:52,720
and have them run independently,

88
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:55,040
but you would prefer them to be able to communicate

89
00:04:55,040 --> 00:04:57,040
and have some shared structure.

90
00:04:57,040 --> 00:05:00,000
Now, they can communicate anyway through .md files

91
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:01,839
if you did have them as separate terminals,

92
00:05:01,839 --> 00:05:04,399
but it would be a little bit flaky.

93
00:05:04,399 --> 00:05:07,279
It would depend a lot on who's writing what to which file

94
00:05:07,359 --> 00:05:08,880
rather than reading them again.

95
00:05:08,880 --> 00:05:12,399
So this way, you could have different Claude code instances

96
00:05:12,399 --> 00:05:13,839
working on different modules,

97
00:05:13,839 --> 00:05:16,239
but still working in lockstep,

98
00:05:16,239 --> 00:05:18,399
still having a channel of communication.

99
00:05:18,399 --> 00:05:20,559
And then the other way is kind of similar,

100
00:05:20,559 --> 00:05:23,040
but it's saying rather than dividing them vertically

101
00:05:23,040 --> 00:05:25,200
into different areas of responsibility,

102
00:05:25,200 --> 00:05:29,279
you could divide them horizontally by layer,

103
00:05:29,279 --> 00:05:30,160
by coding layer,

104
00:05:30,160 --> 00:05:32,239
like you could have a front-end engineer,

105
00:05:32,239 --> 00:05:34,720
back-end engineer, LLM engineer,

106
00:05:34,720 --> 00:05:38,239
responsible for different areas of your system.

107
00:05:38,239 --> 00:05:40,399
And that does translate quite nicely

108
00:05:40,399 --> 00:05:42,079
to the way that you sometimes organize humans

109
00:05:42,079 --> 00:05:43,359
in a software engineering team,

110
00:05:43,359 --> 00:05:46,320
that you can do it by area, by feature,

111
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:48,160
by feature area of your system,

112
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:50,079
or you can do it into a front-end team

113
00:05:50,079 --> 00:05:51,760
and a back-end team and so on.

114
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:53,839
And, you know, I always hesitate

115
00:05:53,839 --> 00:05:57,359
before ascribing too much human-like responsibility to agents,

116
00:05:57,359 --> 00:05:59,600
but you can see how this works quite well

117
00:05:59,600 --> 00:06:02,559
in terms of having separate responsibilities

118
00:06:02,559 --> 00:06:04,959
that cloud code instances can work on independently

119
00:06:04,959 --> 00:06:06,559
without too much overlap.

120
00:06:06,559 --> 00:06:07,760
And you're probably getting the idea

121
00:06:07,760 --> 00:06:10,239
that there's a lot of experimentation involved

122
00:06:10,239 --> 00:06:12,160
in getting agent teams to work well.

123
00:06:12,160 --> 00:06:14,320
There's not necessarily one right answer.

124
00:06:14,320 --> 00:06:16,480
It needs some balance.

125
00:06:16,480 --> 00:06:18,480
You're ideally looking to be able to give

126
00:06:18,480 --> 00:06:20,720
separate responsibilities to cloud agents

127
00:06:20,720 --> 00:06:22,799
so that they can work independently

128
00:06:22,799 --> 00:06:25,359
and still have some benefit to communication

129
00:06:25,359 --> 00:06:28,079
between the agents so they can collaborate,

130
00:06:28,079 --> 00:06:29,679
but not so much communication

131
00:06:29,679 --> 00:06:31,679
that they start to grind down

132
00:06:31,679 --> 00:06:34,320
and they're churning with lots of backwards and forwards.

133
00:06:34,320 --> 00:06:36,000
So you're looking to strike that balance.

134
00:06:36,640 --> 00:06:39,359
And Anthropic's website is really good on this.

135
00:06:39,359 --> 00:06:41,679
It's got some very clear instructions

136
00:06:41,679 --> 00:06:44,480
and they may have changed since I'm doing this.

137
00:06:44,480 --> 00:06:46,079
It's probably worth a look.

138
00:06:46,079 --> 00:06:47,600
It's got this nice table in there

139
00:06:47,600 --> 00:06:50,799
that compares sub-agents to agent teams,

140
00:06:50,799 --> 00:06:52,559
these two techniques.

141
00:06:52,559 --> 00:06:56,160
And it's pretty clear that they are very different

142
00:06:56,160 --> 00:06:57,679
and they each have their place,

143
00:06:57,679 --> 00:07:00,880
sub-agents where they have their own context,

144
00:07:00,880 --> 00:07:02,559
they return it to the caller,

145
00:07:02,559 --> 00:07:07,200
the communication is only back to their main agent.

146
00:07:07,200 --> 00:07:09,440
The main agent manages all the work.

147
00:07:09,440 --> 00:07:11,440
They have focused tasks

148
00:07:11,440 --> 00:07:14,320
and they basically summarize the results back

149
00:07:14,320 --> 00:07:17,119
so they're quite efficient from a token point of view.

150
00:07:17,119 --> 00:07:19,839
They can cause more tokens to be spent themselves,

151
00:07:19,839 --> 00:07:21,279
but they're relatively efficient.

152
00:07:21,920 --> 00:07:26,480
Agent teams, they have their own full context window

153
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:28,640
that is completely independent.

154
00:07:28,640 --> 00:07:30,799
They don't return it to the caller.

155
00:07:31,440 --> 00:07:34,399
They can message the other teammates independently.

156
00:07:34,399 --> 00:07:37,040
They have a shared task list.

157
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:40,160
There is one task list that is managed

158
00:07:40,160 --> 00:07:43,679
by the overall, by the main Claude code,

159
00:07:43,679 --> 00:07:47,200
and they coordinate their items on the task list.

160
00:07:47,200 --> 00:07:49,839
They're best for when there is complex work

161
00:07:49,839 --> 00:07:52,079
that does require a level of collaboration,

162
00:07:52,079 --> 00:07:53,440
but not too much.

163
00:07:53,440 --> 00:07:55,200
And they can be expensive.

164
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:57,279
They can cause a lot of tokens to be spent.

165
00:07:57,279 --> 00:07:58,880
So you need to be aware of that.

166
00:07:58,880 --> 00:08:01,200
And look at that last bullet there.

167
00:08:01,200 --> 00:08:03,359
Use sub-agents when you need quick,

168
00:08:03,359 --> 00:08:05,600
focused workers that report back.

169
00:08:05,600 --> 00:08:08,880
Use agent teams when teammates need to share findings,

170
00:08:09,440 --> 00:08:12,640
challenge each other, and coordinate on their own.

171
00:08:12,640 --> 00:08:15,200
Okay, there are five instructions

172
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:16,559
that we will go through now.

173
00:08:16,559 --> 00:08:18,160
It's time for us to do this.

174
00:08:18,160 --> 00:08:21,200
Five steps to making the Claude agent teams work.

175
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:23,040
First of all, we need to change

176
00:08:23,040 --> 00:08:25,200
settings.json for the project.

177
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:28,079
We need to tell it that we are going to enable

178
00:08:28,079 --> 00:08:30,320
Claude code experimental agent teams.

179
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:31,600
You might not need to do this

180
00:08:31,600 --> 00:08:33,280
because it might then be fully live

181
00:08:33,280 --> 00:08:35,200
without needing this flag, but we do.

182
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:37,679
There's another field as well called teammate mode.

183
00:08:37,679 --> 00:08:39,200
And there are two modes.

184
00:08:39,200 --> 00:08:40,880
And one of them, in process,

185
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:43,599
works on all computers, on Mac and PC.

186
00:08:43,599 --> 00:08:45,679
And it just means that all of the agents

187
00:08:45,679 --> 00:08:47,440
report back in the same screen.

188
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:48,479
And you can flip between them

189
00:08:48,479 --> 00:08:49,919
by pressing shift up and down.

190
00:08:49,919 --> 00:08:51,119
And that's what we'll use.

191
00:08:51,119 --> 00:08:54,320
There is a cooler approach called Teamux.

192
00:08:54,880 --> 00:08:57,599
But that only works on Macs and Linux

193
00:08:57,599 --> 00:08:59,679
when you have extra stuff installed.

194
00:08:59,679 --> 00:09:01,440
And so I'm not going to do it.

195
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:03,200
But if you wish, you could try that.

196
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:03,840
And when you do that,

197
00:09:03,840 --> 00:09:06,479
your screen splits into different sections.

198
00:09:06,479 --> 00:09:08,320
And you can see each of the different agents

199
00:09:08,320 --> 00:09:09,119
in a different section.

200
00:09:09,119 --> 00:09:10,400
And that's pretty cool.

201
00:09:10,400 --> 00:09:11,440
So you might want to do that

202
00:09:11,440 --> 00:09:12,640
if you want to see that yourself.

203
00:09:12,640 --> 00:09:14,880
You have to change in process to Teamux

204
00:09:14,880 --> 00:09:17,119
and you have to have the Teamux installed

205
00:09:17,119 --> 00:09:18,880
or be using something called iTerm2

206
00:09:18,880 --> 00:09:19,840
if you know what that is.

207
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:22,320
So this is what we're going to put in settings.json.

208
00:09:22,320 --> 00:09:23,840
And this should work on all platforms.

209
00:09:23,840 --> 00:09:26,000
And then it's just as simple as prompting Claude

210
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:30,000
to say create an agent team to blah, blah, blah.

211
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:31,760
And you can give it a lot of detail

212
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:33,599
and tell it how the agent should be made up

213
00:09:33,599 --> 00:09:34,719
or the team should be made up

214
00:09:34,719 --> 00:09:36,479
or you can just give it the instruction.

215
00:09:37,039 --> 00:09:38,960
You can then press shift tab

216
00:09:38,960 --> 00:09:40,400
to turn it into delegate mode.

217
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:41,440
That's something worth doing

218
00:09:41,440 --> 00:09:43,440
to make sure that the main agent

219
00:09:43,440 --> 00:09:48,640
doesn't just start handling the tasks itself.

220
00:09:48,640 --> 00:09:50,320
And you can also, if necessary,

221
00:09:50,320 --> 00:09:52,159
prompt it, wait for your teammates

222
00:09:52,159 --> 00:09:54,080
to complete their tasks before proceeding

223
00:09:54,080 --> 00:09:56,400
to stop it diving in and doing work itself.

224
00:09:56,400 --> 00:09:58,960
Anthropic mentions that that's a common problem.

225
00:09:59,520 --> 00:10:00,880
And then shift up and down

226
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:02,799
is how you flip between the different teammates.

227
00:10:03,359 --> 00:10:05,119
And when you're done,

228
00:10:05,119 --> 00:10:06,799
you send a command,

229
00:10:06,799 --> 00:10:10,159
ask the blah teammate to shut down

230
00:10:10,159 --> 00:10:12,640
as a way to tell the main agent

231
00:10:12,640 --> 00:10:14,400
that it should shut down one of the team members.

232
00:10:14,960 --> 00:10:16,479
And then clean up the team

233
00:10:16,479 --> 00:10:19,200
is a general command to stop everything.

234
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:21,280
So we need to know these commands,

235
00:10:21,919 --> 00:10:23,039
these are the instructions

236
00:10:23,039 --> 00:10:26,159
for successfully running an agent team in Cloud Code.

237
00:10:26,159 --> 00:10:27,679
And as three final bits of advice

238
00:10:27,679 --> 00:10:28,880
before we go and do this,

239
00:10:28,880 --> 00:10:30,880
we should invest in cloud.md.

240
00:10:30,880 --> 00:10:33,440
That gets loaded into the context for everything.

241
00:10:33,440 --> 00:10:36,080
And so it's our opportunity to make sure

242
00:10:36,080 --> 00:10:39,039
that all the agents start with the right information.

243
00:10:39,679 --> 00:10:41,599
And we need to expect this to be pricey.

244
00:10:42,159 --> 00:10:44,400
If you try and use free models for this,

245
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:45,200
you could give it a shot,

246
00:10:45,200 --> 00:10:48,159
but I imagine it's just not going to be reliable.

247
00:10:48,880 --> 00:10:50,320
So if you're not comfortable with the cost,

248
00:10:50,320 --> 00:10:52,799
just watch me use this as a learning experience

249
00:10:52,799 --> 00:10:54,320
from seeing someone else doing it.

250
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:56,400
If you're okay to go for this,

251
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:57,919
then do expect a cost.

252
00:10:57,919 --> 00:10:59,039
Watch your costs.

253
00:10:59,039 --> 00:11:01,359
Stop it if you ever become uncomfortable.

254
00:11:01,359 --> 00:11:04,559
And also to add salt to the wound,

255
00:11:05,200 --> 00:11:08,080
you do need to be willing to rerun the whole thing.

256
00:11:08,080 --> 00:11:09,280
It might go off the rails.

